    {
      "id": 2,
      "title": "Quadratic Graphs — Three Forms",
      "kind": "concept",
      "narration": "Quadratics come in three forms. General form gives the y-intercept c. Factorized form gives x-intercepts alpha and beta. Completed square form gives the turning point h comma k.",
      "blocks": [
        {
          "type": "heading",
          "text": "Quadratic Graphs",
          "reveal_at_seconds": 0
        },
        {
          "type": "bullet",
          "text": "General Form: Read y-intercept c",
          "reveal_at_seconds": 3
        },
        {
          "type": "math",
          "latex": "y = ax^2 + bx + c",
          "reveal_at_seconds": 3
        },
        {
          "type": "bullet",
          "text": "Factorized Form: Read x-intercepts α and β",
          "reveal_at_seconds": 7
        },
        {
          "type": "math",
          "latex": "y = (x - \\alpha)(x - \\beta)",
          "reveal_at_seconds": 7
        },
        {
          "type": "bullet",
          "text": "Completed Square Form: Read turning point (h, k)",
          "reveal_at_seconds": 11
        },
        {
          "type": "math",
          "latex": "y = a(x - h)^2 + k",
          "reveal_at_seconds": 11
        }
      ],
      "duration_hint_sec": 15,
      "audio": "audio_02.mp3"
    },
    {
      "id": 3,
      "title": "Example: Completing the Square",
      "kind": "example",
      "narration": "Express minus x squared plus six x minus fourteen in completed square form. Factor out the minus one. Complete the square inside. We get minus quantity x minus three squared minus five. For three x squared plus twelve x plus thirteen, factor out the three. Complete the square. We get three times x plus two squared plus one.",
      "blocks": [
        {
          "type": "heading",
          "text": "Example 1: Completing the Square",
          "reveal_at_seconds": 0
        },
        {
          "type": "math",
          "latex": "y = -x^2 + 6x - 14",
          "reveal_at_seconds": 2
        },
        {
          "type": "math",
          "latex": "= -(x^2 - 6x + 14)",
          "reveal_at_seconds": 5
        },
        {
          "type": "math",
          "latex": "= -\\left[ x^2 - 6x + \\left(\\frac{6}{2}\\right)^2 - \\left(\\frac{6}{2}\\right)^2 + 14 \\right]",
          "reveal_at_seconds": 8
        },
        {
          "type": "math",
          "latex": "= -[(x-3)^2 + 5] = -(x-3)^2 - 5",
          "reveal_at_seconds": 12
        },
        {
          "type": "math",
          "latex": "y = 3x^2 + 12x + 13",
          "reveal_at_seconds": 16
        },
        {
          "type": "math",
          "latex": "= 3\\left(x^2 + 4x + \\frac{13}{3}\\right)",
          "reveal_at_seconds": 18
        },
        {
          "type": "math",
          "latex": "= 3\\left[(x+2)^2 + \\frac{1}{3}\\right] = 3(x+2)^2 + 1",
          "reveal_at_seconds": 21
        }
      ],
      "duration_hint_sec": 24,
      "audio": "audio_03.mp3"
    },
    {
      "id": 4,
      "title": "Applications: Projectile Motion",
      "kind": "example",
      "narration": "A stone's height is modeled by h equals minus a x squared plus x plus two over five. Complete the square to find the maximum. We get turning point one over two a comma one over four a plus two over five. Since max height is two point four, solve for a. We get a equals one eighth. Horizontal distance at max is four meters.",
      "blocks": [
        {
          "type": "heading",
          "text": "Applications of Quadratic Functions",
          "reveal_at_seconds": 0
        },
        {
          "type": "math",
          "latex": "h = -ax^2 + x + \\frac{2}{5}",
          "reveal_at_seconds": 2
        },
        {
          "type": "math",
          "latex": "= -a\\left(x - \\frac{1}{2a}\\right)^2 + \\frac{1}{4a} + \\frac{2}{5}",
          "reveal_at_seconds": 7
        },
        {
          "type": "bullet",
          "text": "Max point: (1/(2a), 1/(4a) + 2/5)",
          "reveal_at_seconds": 12
        },
        {
          "type": "math",
          "latex": "\\frac{1}{4a} + \\frac{2}{5} = 2.4 \\implies a = \\frac{1}{8}",
          "reveal_at_seconds": 15
        },
        {
          "type": "bullet",
          "text": "Horizontal distance = 4 m",
          "reveal_at_seconds": 19
        }
      ],
      "duration_hint_sec": 22,
      "audio": "audio_04.mp3"
    },
    {
      "id": 5,
      "title": "Nature of Roots — Discriminant",
      "kind": "concept",
      "narration": "The discriminant b squared minus four a c tells us the number of roots. If positive, two distinct real roots. If zero, one repeated root. If negative, no real roots.",
      "blocks": [
        {
          "type": "heading",
          "text": "Nature of Roots (Using Discriminant)",
          "reveal_at_seconds": 0
        },
        {
          "type": "bullet",
          "text": "Distinct real roots: b² − 4ac > 0",
          "reveal_at_seconds": 4
        },
        {
          "type": "bullet",
          "text": "Equal real roots: b² − 4ac = 0",
          "reveal_at_seconds": 8
        },
        {
          "type": "bullet",
          "text": "No real roots: b² − 4ac < 0",
          "reveal_at_seconds": 12
        }
      ],
      "duration_hint_sec": 15,
      "audio": "audio_05.mp3"
    },
    {
      "id": 6,
      "title": "Example: Finding Smallest p",
      "kind": "example",
      "narration": "Find smallest positive integer p such that four times p x minus four equals x squared has real roots. Rearrange to x squared minus four p x plus sixteen equals zero. For real roots, discriminant greater or equal zero. Sixteen p squared minus sixty four greater or equal zero. Factorize to get p minus two times p plus two greater or equal zero. So p less or equal minus two or p greater or equal two. Smallest positive integer is two.",
      "blocks": [
        {
          "type": "heading",
          "text": "Example: Applying Discriminant",
          "reveal_at_seconds": 0
        },
        {
          "type": "math",
          "latex": "4(px - 4) = x^2",
          "reveal_at_seconds": 2
        },
        {
          "type": "math",
          "latex": "x^2 - 4px + 16 = 0",
          "reveal_at_seconds": 5
        },
        {
          "type": "math",
          "latex": "b^2 - 4ac \\geq 0",
          "reveal_at_seconds": 8
        },
        {
          "type": "math",
          "latex": "(-4p)^2 - 4(1)(16) \\geq 0",
          "reveal_at_seconds": 10
        },
        {
          "type": "math",
          "latex": "16p^2 - 64 \\geq 0 \\implies p^2 - 4 \\geq 0",
          "reveal_at_seconds": 13
        },
        {
          "type": "math",
          "latex": "(p-2)(p+2) \\geq 0",
          "reveal_at_seconds": 16
        },
        {
          "type": "bullet",
          "text": "p ≤ −2 or p ≥ 2. Smallest positive integer: p = 2",
          "reveal_at_seconds": 19
        },
        {
          "type": "callout",
          "kind": "warning",
          "text": "Common mistake: p² ≥ 4 does NOT give p ≥ ±2",
          "reveal_at_seconds": 22
        }
      ],
      "duration_hint_sec": 25,
      "audio": "audio_06.mp3"
    },
    {
      "id": 7,
      "title": "Inequalities: Similar but Different",
      "kind": "pitfall",
      "narration": "Two inequalities look alike but solve differently. Part a: x squared plus x minus two less than two times x minus one squared. Rearrange and factorize to get x less than one or x greater than four. Part b: x squared plus a x minus two less than two times x minus one squared for all x. Now discriminant must be negative. We get minus eight less than a less than zero.",
      "blocks": [
        {
          "type": "heading",
          "text": "These Two Inequalities Look Alike, But..",
          "reveal_at_seconds": 0
        },
        {
          "type": "math",
          "latex": "x^2 + x - 2 < 2(x-1)^2",
          "reveal_at_seconds": 2
        },
        {
          "type": "math",
          "latex": "x^2 - 5x + 4 > 0 \\implies (x-4)(x-1) > 0",
          "reveal_at_seconds": 6
        },
        {
          "type": "bullet",
          "text": "(a) x < 1 or x > 4",
          "reveal_at_seconds": 10
        },
        {
          "type": "math",
          "latex": "x^2 + ax - 2 < 2(x-1)^2 \\text{ for all } x",
          "reveal_at_seconds": 13
        },
        {
          "type": "math",
          "latex": "-x^2 + (a+4)x - 4 < 0",
          "reveal_at_seconds": 16
        },
        {
          "type": "math",
          "latex": "(a+4)^2 - 4(-1)(-4) < 0 \\implies a^2 + 8a < 0",
          "reveal_at_seconds": 19
        },
        {
          "type": "bullet",
          "text": "(b) −8 < a < 0",
          "reveal_at_seconds": 23
        }
      ],
      "duration_hint_sec": 25,
      "audio": "audio_07.mp3"
    },
    {
      "id": 8,
      "title": "Key Takeaways",
      "kind": "outro",
      "narration": "Remember: complete the square to find turning points. Use discriminant for number of roots. And when an inequality holds for all x, use discriminant conditions. Practice the worked examples to cement these techniques.",
      "blocks": [
        {
          "type": "heading",
          "text": "Summary",
          "reveal_at_seconds": 0
        },
